name: 2-Chloro-4-nitroaniline
Reason: The basic unit here is aniline, which has a melting point of around -6.0°C. Each substituent on the aromatic ring will affect the melting point. The amino group (-NH2) of aniline raises the melting point due to the capacity for hydrogen bonding, which is already factored into the basic unit. A chlorine (Cl) substituent is electron-withdrawing and will increase the melting point of the compound by enhancing the stability of the crystal lattice via stronger intermolecular dipole-dipole interactions; this could increase the melting point by about 40.0°C. The nitro group (NO2) is also electron-withdrawing and will further increase the melting point due to similar stabilization of the crystal lattice. The individual increase due to a nitro group might be approximately 50.0°C since it also introduces possibilities for hydrogen bonding. Combining these effects, we predict a relatively significant increase in melting point over aniline.
